<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--                       ACT 2 — WALT                          -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

:: — ACT 2 — Walt — Good Path {"position":"700,2400","size":"100,100"}
6:15 AM.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/5.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

Walter Hartwell White catalogs his body the way he catalogs everything — systematically, without sentiment. Left knee. The nausea that hasn't arrived yet but will. The particular quality of the morning light that he has started to associate with the first hour of chemo weeks.

Skyler's side of the bed is empty. Flynn left early.
He showers. Thinks about the cook schedule, then Jesse, then Jane — and notices that he's been avoiding saying her name even in his own head and he knows exactly why.

He drives to school. Watches a kid cross at a red light. Wonders, briefly, if the kid has ever bought from one of his dealers. Understands that this thought used to horrify him. Now it's just math.

The difference between those two things is what he can't look at directly.
After fifth period his phone buzzes. Jesse. Crying, or close enough.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/7.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

Combo is dead. Shot on a corner. Had product on him.

Walt processes it: a distribution node, removed. He tells Jesse to stay inside and hangs up, then sits with the clinical efficiency of that thought for the rest of the afternoon.

He isn't sure when he became someone who thinks like this. He's fairly sure he can't go back.
He drives to Jesse's apartment after dark.

He sits in the Aztek on the curb for eleven minutes. He tells himself he's deciding what to say. He isn't. He's stalling. He has been stalling since the moment he agreed to cook in an RV in the desert and called it a plan.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/6.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

He goes in. Door unlocked.
<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/8.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

Jesse is on the bed. Jane is beside him, both on their backs, both breathing.

Except — Jane isn't.

Walt crosses the room in three steps. He knows exactly what this is. He's a chemist. He understands the mechanism perfectly. Roll her to her side, she lives. Don't, she doesn't.

His hand reaches out.

[[Roll her over]]
[[Don't]]


:: — ACT 2 — Walt — Bad Path {"position":"1000,2400","size":"100,100"}
6:15 AM.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/5.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

Walt catalogs his body: left knee, morning nausea pending, chemo fatigue sitting in his shoulders like wet sand. Skyler's side of the bed empty. Flynn gone early.

He showers. Thinks about Jesse — the way Jesse always needs managing. The way Combo's death is going to require managing. The way Jane is going to require managing.

He drives to school. Watches a kid cross at a red light. The thought arrives and departs cleanly: *I wonder if he's ever bought from my operation.* Not horror. Not pride. Just math.
Jesse calls after fifth period. Crying. Combo is dead. Walt tells him to stay put and hangs up and spends the rest of the day being very good at chemistry in front of twenty-three teenagers.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/7.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

He drives to Jesse's apartment after dark. Sits in the Aztek on the curb.

He tells himself he's thinking about what to say. He isn't. He's thinking about Jane. About the fact that she knows too much. About the fact that Jesse won't let go of her on his own.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/6.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

He goes in. Door unlocked.
<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/8.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

Jesse is on the bed. Jane is beside him.

Jane is choking.

Walt crosses the room in three steps. He's a chemist. He knows the mechanism. Roll her to her side, she lives. Don't, she doesn't.

His hand reaches out.

[[Roll her over]]
[[Don't]]


:: Roll her over {"position":"575,2575","size":"100,100"}
(set: $janeLives to true)
His hand keeps moving.

He turns her. She coughs — wet and awful, a sound with no dignity in it at all — and then she breathes.

Walt sits back against the wall, shaking.
He looks at the girl. He looks at his hand. He thinks: *I wanted her dead. I know I did. I sat in that car and I thought about it and I wanted it.*

He also just saved her.

He pulls a blanket over both of them. Turns off the TV. Leaves the door as he found it.

In the hallway he leans against the wall and breathes for a long time.

Whatever he's becoming — he stopped it tonight. Just for tonight.
He drives home. Skyler is asleep on the couch. He stands in the doorway. He considers waking her and saying *I did something tonight.* He doesn't.

He drinks a glass of water in the dark kitchen.

He thinks: tomorrow Saul is going to call.

[[— ACT 3 — Saul — Jane Alive]]


:: Don't {"position":"825,2575","size":"100,100"}
(set: $janeLives to false)
His hand stops.

There are two voices.

One is screaming.

The other is quieter and more reasonable, and it talks about blackmail, about Jesse, about the fact that the universe is handling a problem he doesn't have the stomach for, and about how if he interferes now he is choosing her over everything he has built and everyone who depends on it.

The second voice wins. Not by much. But it wins.
She stops making sounds.

He stands. Walks out. He doesn't remember driving home.

Skyler is asleep on the couch. He stands in the doorway and doesn't go in.

He drinks a glass of water in the dark kitchen and stares at his hand on the glass.

He thinks: tomorrow Saul is going to call.

[[— ACT 3 — Saul — Jane Dead]]


<!-- ============================================================ -->
<!--                      ACT 3 — SAUL                           -->
<!-- ============================================================ -->

<!-- ★ CUTSCENE 3 marker — see notes at bottom of file ★ -->

:: — ACT 3 — Saul — Jane Dead {"position":"900,2700","size":"100,100"}
Dawn at the strip mall.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/9.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

Saul Goodman — real name James McGill, age undisclosed, height whatever the shoes say — unlocks Saul Goodman and Associates.

There are no associates.

He flips on the lights. The Statue of Liberty inflatable on the roof hisses awake through the ceiling. He brews what he calls constitutional coffee, which is just the cheapest grounds at the QuikMart run through twice.

He feels the call coming the way old men feel weather.

The burner has three missed calls from HEISENBERG.
Two from KID.

He stares at both names for a long time.

*Who do you call first?*

[[Call Heisenberg - Jane Dead]]
[[Call the Kid First - Jane Dead]]


:: Call the Kid First - Jane Dead {"position":"750,2850","size":"100,100"}
Voicemail. Of course.

Saul leaves a message in the voice he uses when he's trying to sound calm and isn't:

"Call me back before you call anyone else. That includes nine-one-one. *Especially* nine-one-one. Don't touch anything. Don't talk to anyone. Just — call me back."

He hangs up and calls Heisenberg.

Walt picks up on the first ring.

*"The girl is dead."*

Three words. Flat. Like a man reporting weather.

Saul absorbs it the way he absorbs most things — by not absorbing it at all, by filing it immediately into the professional column.

"Go home. Shower. Kiss your wife. Go to work tomorrow. I'll handle the rest."

He hangs up. Calls Mike.

[[The Mike Call - Jane Dead]]


:: Call Heisenberg - Jane Dead {"position":"1050,2850","size":"100,100"}
Walt picks up on the first ring.

*"The girl is dead."*

Three words. Flat. Not grief. Not panic. Just — information.

Saul absorbs it the way he absorbs most things — by not absorbing it at all.

"Go home," Saul says. "Shower. Kiss your wife. Go to work tomorrow. I'll handle the rest."

He hangs up and tries the Kid.

Voicemail. He leaves a message. Calls Mike.

[[The Mike Call - Jane Dead]]


:: The Mike Call - Jane Dead {"position":"900,3000","size":"100,100"}
Thirty seconds flat.

Address. Apartment number. Specific situation.

Mike doesn't do small talk.

"The kid in the apartment too?"

Saul hears what's inside the question.

"Do NOT touch the kid."

"I'm not going to touch the kid, Saul."

Mike hangs up. Saul realizes his hand is shaking on the receiver.

He didn't think Mike would. But he had to say it. That small moment — the fact that he had to say it — is the first crack this morning.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
  <iframe src="Videos/10.mp4" width="600" height="400" style="max-width:90%; border:0; border-radius:8px;" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</div>

Hours pass. Saul doesn't leave the office.

He watches the Statue of Liberty inflate and deflate through the window. He thinks about how every small professional compromise lines up behind you like cars on a highway until you can't see where the road started.

The burner rings. It's the Kid.

[[Jesse Calls - Jane Dead]]


:: Jesse Calls - Jane Dead {"position":"900,3150","size":"100,100"}
Jesse is crying so hard Saul can't understand him for thirty seconds.

"I know," Saul says. "I already know. Listen to me. There's a guy coming to take care of everything. His name doesn't matter. He's going to make this look like what it is — an overdose. Because it *was* an overdose."

Jesse starts to ask *did Mr. White —*

"Motel. East side. Now. I'll come to you."

Jesse goes quiet. "Okay."

Saul sits in the car outside the motel for four minutes before going in.

He tells himself he's thinking about what to say. He isn't. He's been stalling his whole career.

[[The Motel Room - Jane Dead]]


:: The Motel Room - Jane Dead {"position":"900,3300","size":"100,100"}
Jesse is sitting on the edge of the bed with his hands clasped between his knees.

For one second he looks like a kid sent to the principal's office.

Then Saul looks at his face again and it's nothing like that. It's grief so raw it hasn't found a shape yet.

Saul pulls up the one chair. They sit in silence.

Then Jesse says, very quietly:

*"I think I killed her."*

Saul sees his two options with perfect clarity.

He can tell Jesse what he suspects — that Walt was there, that Walt let it happen, that a girl choked to death because she was inconvenient.

Or he can let Jesse carry it. Easier. Cleaner. Better for the retainer.

*What do you tell him?*

[[Let Jesse Believe It - Jane Dead]]
[[Tell Jesse the Truth - Jane Dead]]


:: Let Jesse Believe It - Jane Dead {"position":"700,3475","size":"100,100"}
"Addicts die, Jesse. It's what happens. She rolled the wrong way. You couldn't have known. You couldn't have stopped it."

Jesse nods. He isn't hearing the words. He's hearing the permission to hate himself — something that makes the grief make sense by giving it an address.

Saul watches it settle on him like a coat.

"I know a place past Los Lunas. Takes cash, no questions. You go in, you get clean, you come out the other side."

"...okay."

In the parking lot, Saul stands next to his car for a full minute.

He did the professional thing. He also just handed a kid the straps on something that wasn't his to carry.

He gets in the car.

[[Saul's Decision - Bad Path]]


:: Saul's Decision - Bad Path {"position":"700,3625","size":"100,100"}
Three days later, Walt calls.

Gus Fring. Industrial scale. The kind of operation where there's no walking back.

*What do you do?*

[[Broker the Gus Deal - Bad Ending]]
[[Warn Jesse Instead - Bad Ending]]


:: Broker the Gus Deal - Bad Ending {"position":"550,3775","size":"100,100"}
Saul makes the introduction.

He tells himself it's just business.

He's still telling himself things when the DEA starts watching the laundry. When Gus dies. When the cartel burns. When Jack Welker's crew takes over.

Jesse doesn't get out.

Jack's men find him. Put him in a hole. Make him cook. He cooks the best meth in the country in a cage with a chain around his ankle and a photo of Andrea and Brock on the wall that he isn't allowed to touch.

<div style="text-align:center; margin:20px 0;">
